{"title":"Strade Bianche tech gallery | Tubeless tyres dominate, GRX Di2 for Peter Sagan and a dropper post cameo","link":"https://www.bikeradar.com/features/pro-bike/2023-strade-bianche-tech-gallery/","date":1678204816000,"content":"<img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=620,413\" srcset=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=45&amp;resize=1440,959 1440w, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=45&amp;resize=1200,799 1200w, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=960,639 960w, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=720,479 720w, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=576,383 576w, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=360,239 360w, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2023-682e8d9.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=180,119 180w\" width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt=\"Strade Bianche tech gallery 2023\" title=\"Strade Bianche tech gallery 2023\" />                                            <p><span>Tyres are a hot topic at the top level of professional cycling, not least through the spring when riders face the cobbles of northern Europe and, on Saturday, the white gravel roads of Italy’s Strade Bianche.</span></p>\n<p><span>We were at the </span><i><span>partenza</span></i><span> in Siena to prowl the start pen, roaming the team buses to take a closer look at the key tech choices ahead of Tom Pidcock’s solo victory. </span></p>\n<p><span>Here’s what we spotted, including the near-ubiquitous adoption of <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/tubeless/\">tubeless tyres</a>, the return of Matej Mohorič’s dropper post, a curious spec choice from Peter Sagan and bespoke nutrition plans.</span></p>\n<h2>Tubeless tyres dominate</h2>\n<p><span>Let’s start with tyres – a key talking point at a race such as Strade Bianche, with its 63km of gravel roads. </span></p>\n<p><span>Here, the additional clearance of the latest race bikes comes to the fore, with 28c and 30c tyres specced across the board.</span></p>\n<p><span>Perhaps unsurprisingly, given the rise of tubeless tyres in the pro peloton, and particularly in the Classics, tubeless also dominated in Italy.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <i></i>\n    <div>\n  <div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-73-6516cae.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Pirelli P Zero tubular tyres on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" title=\"Pirelli P Zero tubular tyres on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Greg van Avermaet’s AG2R Citroën team stuck with tubulars in the form of Pirelli’s P Zero Race Tub SL.<br /></span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-3-ae975f7.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Tyre clearance on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" title=\"Tyre clearance on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Having been released in 2020, the current Teammachine’s maximum tyre clearance of 30mm is fairly narrow by today’s standards. Former Olympic champion van Avermaet used 28c tyres for Strade Bianche.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-4-91294fe.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" title=\"AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>All AG2R Citroën riders were on the BMC Teammachine.<br /></span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-2-b1baac1.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Campagnolo Super Record EPS groupset on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" title=\"Campagnolo Super Record EPS groupset on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine bikes at Strade Bianche\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>The French team is the only men’s WorldTour squad sponsored by Campagnolo.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-6-0046e86.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Allen keys strapped to seatpost on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine\" title=\"Allen keys strapped to seatpost on AG2R Citreon's BMC Teammachine\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>An Allen key taped to the seat tube enables the rider to remove the thru-axle in the event of a puncture.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n      </div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p><span>However, Greg van Avermaet’s AG2R Citroën team was a notable outlier, sticking to Pirelli’s P Zero Race Tub SL.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <i></i>\n    <div>\n  <div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-27-f879b1f.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Trek Emonda at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Trek Emonda at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Trek-Segafredo used Pirelli’s P Zero Race TLR tubeless tyres.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-28-49391e9.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Time pedal and SRAM crankset on Trek Emonda at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Time pedal and SRAM crankset on Trek Emonda at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Trek-Segafredo riders are using Time pedals in 2023, marking a return to the peloton for the iconic French company, bought by SRAM in 2023.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n      </div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p><span>Another Pirelli-sponsored team, Trek-Segafredo, did go tubeless with the P Zero Race TLR.</span></p>\n<p><span>Elsewhere, Tom Pidcock used 30c Continental GP 5000 S TR tubeless tyres, the go-to tyre of choice across Continental’s sponsored teams.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <i></i>\n    <div>\n  <div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-29-3930297.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Tom Pidcock's Pinarello Dogma F at Strade Bianche\" title=\"Tom Pidcock's Pinarello Dogma F at Strade Bianche\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Tom Pidcock’s race-winning Pinarello Dogma F, with 30c Continental GP 5000 S TR tubeless tyres.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-30-0a1720c.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Continental GP 5000 S TR tubeless tyre with tan sidewall at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Continental GP 5000 S TR tubeless tyre with tan sidewall at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Conti’s GP 5000 S TR is also available in a tan sidewall option.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-10-cbfa08b.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Continental GP 5000 S TR tubeless tyre on Zipp 303 Firecrest wheel at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Continental GP 5000 S TR tubeless tyre on Zipp 303 Firecrest wheel at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Movistar were also among the teams using Continental’s flagship road tubeless tyre, mounted to Zipp 303 Firecrest wheel.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-11-c08006c.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Canyon Ultimate CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Canyon Ultimate CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>All Movistar riders were on the Canyon Aeroad aero bike, except for Carlos Verona, who opted for the new Canyon Ultimate CFR all-rounder.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n      </div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p><span>Team Ineos opted for Shimano’s Dura-Ace C36 wheels over the rolling hills of Tuscany, while Movistar also kept things shallow with Zipp’s 303 Firecrest wheels, also mounted with Continental’s GP 5000 S TR.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Specialized’s S-Works Turbo 2BR tubeless tyre is now available with a tan sidewall. This 28c tyre is fitted to Peter Sagan’s bike.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p>We also saw the Specialized S-Works Turbo 2BR tubeless tyre, now offered in a tan sidewall option, on the bikes of Soudal-QuickStep and TotalEnergies.</p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Simon Clarke used the endurance-focused Maxxis Velocita tyre, which features a file tread pattern.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>While the majority of teams and riders opted for race-focused tyres, as you’d expect, Israel-Premier Tech’s Simon Clarke ran Maxxis Velocita tyres – an ‘endurance’ option recommended for ‘pavement/asphalt’ and ‘hard-packed dirt roads’. Strade Bianche, then?</span></p>\n<h2>Vittoria Corsa Pro is ‘30 per cent faster’ than a tubular</h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Vittoria’s new Corsa Pro tubeless tyre is yet to be officially launched. This is Tiesj Benoot’s spare bike.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>We spotted the </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/news/new-tan-wall-vittoria-corsa-pro-tubeless-tyre-spotted/\"><span>new Vittoria Corsa Pro</span></a><span> back in December, and the as-yet-unreleased tubeless tyre was a popular choice at Strade Bianche.</span></p>\n<p><span>It’s being used by teams including Jumbo-Visma, Lotto–Dstny and EF Education–EasyPost, with the latter also using foam tyre liners from Vittoria for run-flat protection.</span></p>\n<p><span>While official details are yet to be confirmed, EF Education–EasyPost’s vice president of operations, Jonathan Breekveldt, told BikeRadar that “the coefficient of rolling resistance has been reduced again”.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> <span>EF Education–EasyPost are also using the new tyre and have tested it to be 30 per cent more efficient than a tubular.</span></span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Breekveldt said the EF team spent five days at Vittoria’s lab in Bergamo to test wheel and tyre combinations at the start of the season. </span></p>\n<p><span>“We invested five days to figure out what the optimum pressure is per tyre model and by rider weight as well. We have three [weight] brackets that our mechanics use for pressure, but at the cobbled races and here the riders might reduce it a little bit.”</span></p>\n<p><span>Breekveldt expects EF Education–EasyPost to stop using tubulars from the middle of the year, if not earlier. “Comparing the coefficient of rolling resistance, this setup is more than 30 per cent more efficient than a tubular,” he said.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <i></i>\n    <div>\n  <div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-12-1bf9653.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Vittoria Corsa Control tyre on Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Vittoria Corsa Control tyre on Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Mathieu van der Poel used the Vittoria Corsa Control.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-74-3440f78.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>The Dutchman’s Canyon Aeroad CFR pops in the morning Italian sun.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-14-458157b.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"3D-printed Wahoo mount on Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"3D-printed Wahoo mount on Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>A 3D-printed out-front mount for van der Poel’s Wahoo computer.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-16-a97544d.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Mathieu van der Poel's Canyon Aeroad CFR at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Van der Poel was unable to notch up a second Strade Bianche win, finishing 15th.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n      </div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p><span>While a number of teams were on the new Corsa Pro, Mathieu van der Poel used Vittoria’s existing Corsa Control tubeless tyre; the same was true of the Astana Qazaqstan team.</span></p>\n<h2>Drop it like it’s hot – until it’s not</h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> <span>Matej Mohorič started the race on a Merida Scultura with a dropper post.</span></span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Matej Mohorič’s dropper post is back.</span></p>\n<p><span>Mohorič made headlines last season by not only winning Milan-San Remo, but by <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/features/pro-bike/matej-mohoric-dropper-post/\">using a dropper post to launch his daredevil attack on the descent of the Poggio</a>.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> A mid-race mechanical required <span>Mohorič to swap to his spare bike, the Merida Reacto, which can’t accept a dropper post.</span></span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>We spotted the Slovenian’s Merida Scultura equipped with a dropper as the team rolled out of the start in Siena. However, after a mechanical during the race, Mohorič swapped to his spare bike, a Merida Reacto, which is unable to accommodate a dropper post.</span></p>\n<p><span>Indeed, while Mohorič’s team-mates were on the Reacto to start, owing to the Reacto’s aero-profiled seatpost, Mohorič needs to ride the Scultura – one of the few bikes in the pro peloton with a standard round post – in order to use a dropper.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> The dusty demands of Strade Bianche.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Will we see Mohorič, who finished sixth at Strade Bianche, back on a dropper-equipped Scultura at Milan-San Remo? We reckon so…</span></p>\n<h2>Nutrition notes</h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> <span>Andreas Kron’s nutrition plan for Strade Bianche.</span></span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Nutrition know-how has improved dramatically among teams and riders in recent years, and that was evidenced in the bespoke nutrition strategies outlined on some bikes.</span></p>\n<p><span>Take Andreas Kron of Lotto–Dstny, who had his food and drink requirements detailed on his stem, with specific timings. The Danish rider also had the race profile – and gravel sectors – on the handlebar.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Mathieu van der Poel’s plan for the day.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Mathieu van der Poel was also among the riders to have his nutrition plan taped to the stem.</span></p>\n<p><span> Once again, it features an outline of his planned hydration and food intake, in addition to the location of each gravel sector.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Some plans are more rudimentary than others.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<h2>Ok, computer</h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> <span>Antonio Nibali prefers the large screen of the Garmin Edge 1040…</span></span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>While computer sponsorship is common among top-tier pro teams, riders can typically choose their preferred model, providing the sponsor offers a range of devices.</span></p>\n<p><span>For example, Astana’s Antonio Nibali used the </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/reviews/training/gps-computers/cycle-computers/garmin-edge-1040-solar-bike-computer-review/\"><span>Garmin Edge 1040</span></a><span>, while his team-mate, Alexey Lutsenko, opted for the much smaller </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/news/garmin-edge-130-plus-1030-plus/\"><span>Garmin Edge 130 Plus</span></a><span>.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> …whereas <span>Alexey Lutsenko uses the compact </span>Garmin Edge 130 Plus.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Some riders only want a device that shows the bare minimum, in terms of data. Others prefer a bigger screen to present more data, or to use the mapping functionality to get an early view on upcoming corners.</span></p>\n<p><span>Wahoo-sponsored teams also give riders the choice between the bigger <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/reviews/training/gps-computers/wahoo-elemnt-roam-v2-review/\">Elemnt Roam</a> and the smaller (though still with mapping) <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/reviews/training/gps-computers/cycle-computers/wahoo-elemnt-bolt-v2-review/\">Elemnt Bolt</a>.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> <span>Israel Premier-Tech riders use the Hammerhead Karoo 2.</span></span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>There’s no such luck for Israel Premier-Tech riders, though. The team is sponsored by Hammerhead, with the upstart only offering the Karoo 2 computer (<a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/reviews/training/gps-computers/cycle-computers/hammerhead-karoo-2-bike-computer-review/\">even if it is very good</a>).</span></p>\n<p><span>One common trend across bikes at Strade Bianche was the use of a lanyard to keep the computer attached to the bike, in the event of it getting dislodged from the out-front mount on rough gravel sectors.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Most computers are supplied with a lanyard/tether, something a lot of riders used at Strade Bianche to keep the unit attached to the bike in case it became dislodged from the mount on rough roads.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<h2><span>GRX Di2 for Peter Sagan</span></h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Peter Sagan’s Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>One of the more curious spec choices at Strade Bianche – and at the Opening Weekend, too – was Peter Sagan’s GRX Di2 derailleur.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> A GRX Di2 rear derailleur and colour-matched CeramicSpeed OSPW setup for Sagan.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>A TotalEnergies staff member told BikeRadar that Sagan prefers the improved chain retention offered by the GRX derailleur, which has a clutch mechanism (though it wasn’t turned on when we shot Sagan’s bike minutes before the race start).</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> This zip-tie keeps the Di2 cable in place in the event of a crash.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>The 11-speed derailleur requires the use of 11-speed components across the rest of the groupset, so it’s Dura-Ace R9100 for the Slovak rider. Check out the oversized – and colour-matched – CeramicSpeed OSPW jockey wheels, too.</span></p>\n<p><span>Like Alaphilippe, Sagan also used the new Specialized S-Works Turbo 2BR tubeless tyre with tan sidewalls, mounted to Roval Rapide CLX wheels. </span></p>\n<div>\n    <i></i>\n    <div>\n  <div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-55-783553b.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Shimano Dura-Ace Di2 crankset on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Shimano Dura-Ace Di2 crankset on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Sagan was running 11-speed Shimano Dura-Ace Di2 R9100 at Strade Bianche.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-62-88a171b.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Sprint shifters on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Sprint shifters on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>The three-time world champion has been a long-time fan of Shimano’s sprint shifters.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-63-7c42b73.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Roval Rapide handlebar on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Roval Rapide handlebar on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>The Roval Rapide handlebar cuts a lean profile.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-61-2af3a4d.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Roval Rapide CLX wheels on Peter Sagan's Specialized Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Roval Rapide CLX wheels on Peter Sagan's Specialized Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Deep-section Roval Rapide CLX wheels for Sagan.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-60-ab5b350.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Bike computer on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Bike computer on Peter Sagan's Specialized S-Works Tarmac SL7 at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>Could Sagan bow out from pro cycling at the end of 2023?</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n      </div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Cannondale makes it official</h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Now official: the fourth-generation Cannondale SuperSix EVO.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/news/2023-cannondale-supersix-evo/\">new Cannondale SuperSix EVO</a> turned out to be one of the most-teased bikes in recent years, with the <span>EF Education–EasyPost team riding the bike towards the end of 2023, months ahead of its launch last week.</span></p>\n<p>Updates to the fourth-generation model include a more aerodynamic frame shape and reduced weight – dropping to 770g for the flagship Lab71 frame used by the team.</p>\n<div>\n    <i></i>\n    <div>\n  <div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-21-6cd9a9e.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Handlebar and stem on a Cannondale SuperSix Evo 4 at Strade Bianche 2023\" title=\"Handlebar and stem on a Cannondale SuperSix Evo 4 at Strade Bianche 2023\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>The new SuperSix can be run with either a two-piece handlebar and stem…</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n          <div>\n        \n<figure><div>\n    <img src=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2023/03/Strade-Bianche-tech-gallery-22-df7d04e.jpg?quality=90&amp;resize=556%2C723\" width=\"556\" height=\"723\" alt=\"Strade Bianche tech gallery_-22\" title=\"Strade Bianche tech gallery_-22\" /></div>    <figcaption><div>\n    <figcaption><span>…or an integrated cockpit.</span>\n    </figcaption><span>\n                    <i>George Scott / Our Media</i>\n            </span>\n</div>\n\n    </figcaption></figure></div>\n      </div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p>There’s also a simplified front-end that gives riders the option to run either an integrated cockpit or a more traditional two-piece setup.</p>\n<p>On that note, six of the team’s seven riders opted for a one-piece bar and stem at Strade Bianche, but Andrey Amador preferred the flexibility offered by pairing an FSA SCR aluminium stem with Vision’s Metron carbon handlebar.</p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Jens Keukeleire was tasked with GoPro duties for <span>EF Education–EasyPost at Strade Bianche.</span></span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<h2><span>Pinot’s palmarès</span></h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Thibaut Pinot’s Lapierre Xelius SL.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Thibaut Pinot’s Lapierre Xelius SL caught our eye – not because of the unique seatstay arrangement, but because of the Frenchman’s key wins, detailed on the top tube.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Pinot’s top tube details the Frenchman’s key wins, including his six Grand Tour victories.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>Those wins include Pinot’s six Grand Tour stages wins – three (2012, 2015, 2019) at the Tour de France, two (2018) at the Giro d’Italia and one (2017) at the Vuelta a España.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> The Xelius SL’s top tube and seatstay arrangement is said to improve comfort.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Who remembers that solo Alpe d’Huez win at the 2015 Tour de France?</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<h2><span>The pick of the bunch</span></h2>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> Very pretty indeed.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>And finally, Astana Qazaqstan’s Wilier 0 SLR is surely the prettiest bike in the WorldTour peloton in 2023.</span></p>\n<p><span>The marble-effect paintjob is stunning in the flesh.</span></p>\n<div>\n    <img width=\"620\" height=\"413\" alt title /></div><div><figcaption><span><i></i> The marble effect is stunning.</span></figcaption><span> <i>George Scott / Our Media</i></span></div>\n<p><span>It’s described as a ‘chrome-plated graphite livery’ by Wilier, starting in the team’s trademark ‘azzurro’ before fading to a darker blue on the seatstays, seat tube and down tube.</span></p>\n<p><span>The 0 SLR is Wilier’s lightweight bike, preferred by the likes of Antonio Nibali, while </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/features/pro-bike/mark-cavendishs-new-wilier-bike-astana-qazaqstan-2023/\"><span>Mark Cavendish is riding the more aerodynamic Filante SLR</span></a><span>.</span></p>","author":"George Scott","siteTitle":"BikeRadar","siteHash":"df99dd1320fcd97327a2def4c67247c08cd4090a7dab684a0eddb9b856f80ef1","entryHash":"5d366ad52fda9516ffd0e4b20a27207ade4abc31323af592b3ff2e55cf9f6fbf","category":"Cycling"}